;; Long comment in port-resolve.lisp ----

;; Port/portdecl/vardecl resoluion is a horrible part of Verilog/SystemVerilog
;; that we handle through a series of hacks.

;; There are effectively two ways to declare ports (a module must use
;; exclusively one or the other):

;;  ANSI: e.g. module foo (input a, output b); ... endmodule
;;  non-ANSI: e.g. module foo (a, b); input a; output b; ... endmodule

;; We process things toward the non-ANSI style, since it has a few features
;; that the ANSI style doesn't (e.g. port expressions that implicitly convert
;; between external and internal names).  In the non-ANSI style, the portlist
;; (a, b) and port declarations (input a; output b;) are separate.

;; In the non-ANSI style, you can have a variable declaration of something that
;; also has a port declaration, provided the port declaration doesn't include a
;; net or variable type.  In the ANSI style, you're technically not supposed to
;; have a variable declaration for something that is also a port.  However, in
;; practice tools tend to accept this, so we'll try to also.

;; We want to process every module to a uniform format which has:
;;    - ports and portdecls, as if in the non-ANSI style
;;    - a variable declaration corresponding to every port declaration.
;; The complications are:
;;    - converting from the ANSI to non-ANSI style
;;    - dealing with incomplete port declarations that have corresponding
;;       variable declarations
;;    - dealing with port declarations that have duplicate variable declarations
;;    - warning on bad cases.

;; We handle these things in a few places.

;; Parser:
;;  - vl-parse-module-port-list-top produces
;;    either a vl-nonansi-ports structure containing a vl-portlist-p obj or a
;;    vl-ansi-ports object containing a vl-ansi-portdecllist obj.

;;  - For nonansi ports, the port declarations are in with the module items.
;; The function vl-make-ports-and-maybe-nets inserts an annotation
;; "VL_INCOMPLETE_DECLARATION" which portdecl-sign looks for in order to
;; determine whether to unify the port and var decls.  But we don't add this
;; annotation for ANSI ports because they should always be complete.

;; For nonansi portdecls, the parser also produces a vardecl for every
;; complete portdecl, but not for incomplete ones.

;; For ansi portdecls, the parser just produces a list of vl-ansi-portdecl
;; objects that are in the ansi-ports sub-fields of the parse-temps field of
;; the module.

;; resolve-ansi-portdecls adds a port and portdecl for each ansi-portdecl from
;; parsing.  Aside from interfaceports, it produces one of each per
;; ansi-portdecl.  We used to add vardecls as well but now we don't; it will
;; get added by vl-make-port-implicit-wires.

;; vl-make-port-implicit-wires looks through a module's elements in reverse
;; parse order (as well as the implicit items generated by
;; make-implicit-wires, at the end), and adds a vardecl for each portdecl
;; that doesn't have a corresponding (moditem) declaration after
;; make-implicit-wires.  The vardecl generated has a "VL_PORT_IMPLICIT"
;; annotation.

;; Portdecl-sign:
;;  - assumes every portdecl has a corresponding vardecl.
;;  - warns if there are multiple vardecls
;;  - unifies incomplete type info between port and var decls when possible.





